<TITLE> Nepal bars 175 troops from UN missions over abuses </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 KATHMANDU, Wed Dec 17,(bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Nepal's army has barred 175 of its troops from participating in UN peacekeeping missions because of human rights abuses committed during a decade-long civil war, a Nepali army general said on Wednesday. Human rights groups accuse government troops of violations such as killings, kidnappings, disappearances and rape during the conflict, in which an estimated people were 13,000 killed. The United Nations had urged Nepal not to offer soldiers guilty of such abuses for its peacekeeping operations. "They are unfit for UN missions," army spokesman Brigadier General Ramindra Chhetri told Reuters. He said officers were among those barred from UN missions. Nepal has contributed some 60,000 troops to 40 UN peacekeeping missions around the world, including Haiti, Congo and Burundi, in the past 50 years. Another army official said the move was part of the Nepal army's "commitment to protect and promote" human rights. "It will raise human rights awareness among soldiers," Brigadier General B.A. Kumar Sharma said. Former Maoist rebels, who are also accused of similar human rights abuses, fought the army for 10 years in a conflict that ended with a 2006 peace deal. They now head a coalition government formed after an April vote for a special assemb
